  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me. Growing up in a family where education wasn't the priority, and with my parents having limited schooling themselves, I never had the same confidence in my academic abilities that my peers did. When I first started working at a local auto shop, I remember feeling nervous about explaining complex mechanics to customers because I'd heard stereotypes about 'men being better at science.' But it wasn't just about gender—it was about the fear of being labeled 'not smart enough' in a field where I felt out of place. Stereotype threat is that anxiety you feel when you're in a situation where your identity is tied to a group that's been unfairly stereotyped. In my case, it's the worry that if I mess up, people will think I'm less capable than someone who fits the 'typical' stereotype. That's why addressing it matters—it's not just about fixing the system but helping people like me feel safe to try. I think the best way to tackle it is by creating inclusive environments where everyone's worth isn't tied to a stereotype. For example, if a shop has a mentorship program that pairs new mechanics with someone who's been through similar struggles, it could help reduce that anxiety. It's about making sure people feel seen and valued, not judged by what they're supposed to be. And honestly, it's not just for STEM—it's for every field where people feel they don't belong.",
